<DOC><DOCNO> DOE2-37-0684 </DOCNO><TEXT>Public confidence in nuclear power was shaken by the Chernobyl accident.However, provided the lessons learned from that incident are seen tohave been learnt, it seems likely that public opinion will swing backin favour of nuclear power. The 1987 Uranium Institute symposium lookedat the world situation by considering the nuclear power programme indifferent countries. The consensus was that the cost of the extra safetyprecautions needed to allay public fears has put the economic case fornuclear power in jeopardy. There has been a major swing towards coalas fuel. The demand for oil and gas as fuels for generating electricityis also growing, influenced by national energy policies, environmentalconsiderations and inter-fuel economics. Although energy conservation,clean combustion technologies and renewable energy sources might contributesignificantly to long term energy supply, only nuclear fission and laterfusion, are viable in the short and medium term. (U.K.).</TEXT></DOC>